1052586099																										1112348										http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/			2014-12-08T00:42Z			http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/1112348				© ozook some rights reserved	ozook												iNaturalist	Observations	iNaturalist research-grade observations		HUMAN_OBSERVATION				http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/1112348	1112348		ozook																Salal is a shrub, creeping to erect with hair branched stems.  The leaves are alternate, deep green and leathery. The edges are finely toothed.  Among the most common  understory shrubs, it can form a layer of continuous shrubbery. 1065582791																										1048390										http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/			2015-02-15T04:52Z			http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/1048390				© artger24 some rights reserved	artger24												iNaturalist	Observations	iNaturalist research-grade observations		HUMAN_OBSERVATION				http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/1048390	1048390		artger24																The salal is a creeping plant that have layers that range from 0.2-5m tall with leaves that appear  evergreen, leathery and alternate as well as thick shiny and egg shaped. They are finely toothed and sharp and range 5-10cm long. The fruits of the salal are using reddish-blue or dark purple and are fleshy sepals that are 6-10mm broad and edible. The flowers are white or pinkish, 7-10mm long, 5-15 of them at the end with bending stalks in one direction.  Salals are usually found at the bottom of forest foliage. 1038343213																										1046665										http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/			2014-11-04T03:36Z			http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/1046665				© irenemoore some rights reserved	irenemoore												iNaturalist	Observations	iNaturalist research-grade observations		HUMAN_OBSERVATION				http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/1046665	1046665		irenemoore																Gaultheria shallon, or Salal, is a durable shrub, native to western North America. It has thick and leathery simple leaves with tiny serrated edges if you look closely. The upper side of the leaves are a dark green and are waxy and glossy from a thick cuticle. Underneath they are a duller, papery pastel green. They are arranged alternately about the branches. It is commonly seen in the under story of larger trees like this Hemlock. Maples surround the Salal shrub also. 												2014-10-30T00:00Z				2014	10	30	2014-10-30															US					Woody residential area- Tumwater							47.02149	-122.92543																																	1861555				2014-10-30T19:53Z				48441								Gaultheria shallon Pursh								Plantae	Tracheophyta	Magnoliopsida	Ericales	Ericaceae	Gaultheria		shallon		SPECIES							50c9509d-22c7-4a22-a47d-8c48425ef4a7	US	2016-06-06T13:55Z							COORDINATE_ROUNDED;GEODETIC_DATUM_ASSUMED_WGS84		true	false	2882758	6	7707728	220	1353	2505	2882751		2882758	Gaultheria shallon	Gaultheria		DWC_ARCHIVE	2016-06-06T13:28Z	2016-06-06T13:28Z	true
